      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Commercial CFD solver with documented QA procedures and version control meets MRL 2 requirements.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2022 R2 is used under a validated installation with institutional license management. Version control logs, regression test suite outputs, and release notes are archived. QA documentation satisfies the Gradation 2 threshold for a Class II MRL 2 assessment."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver passes standard benchmark problems (lid-driven cavity, Taylor-Couette) at required accuracy.",
      "rationale": "Fluent 2022 R2 was verified against the lid-driven cavity benchmark (Re = 1000) and Taylor-Couette flow. Velocity field errors were below 1.2% relative to published reference data. Code verification is judged sufficient for MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) computed on three systematically refined meshes with GCI < 5% on primary QoI (relative hemolysis index RH) at all five operating points.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted on the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry using coarse (2.1 M cells), medium (5.8 M cells), and fine (14.2 M cells) meshes. Richardson extrapolation was applied and GCI values for the relative hemolysis index ranged from 3.1% to 6.8% across the five flow-speed operating points. The two highest-flow operating points (6 L/min at 3500 RPM and 7 L/min at 3500 RPM) exhibited GCI values of 5.9% and 6.8% respectively, marginally exceeding the 5% acceptance threshold. The assessment team notes that these operating points correspond to conditions where hemolysis predictions are conservatively high relative to experimental bench measurements, meaning that any residual discretization error acts in the direction of over-predicting hemolysis rather than under-predicting it. Furthermore, the team has extensive prior experience with this pump geometry across four previous regulatory submissions, and independent expert review by two senior biofluid mechanics engineers confirmed that the mesh density employed is consistent with best practice for turbomachinery hemolysis CFD at MRL 2. Given the conservative directionality of the error, the breadth of supporting experimental correlation, and the expert consensus that the medium mesh captures all flow structures relevant to the hemolysis power-law damage model, the assessment team judges that the discretization evidence is adequate to support the overall Accepted decision despite the formal GCI exceedance at two operating points. A supplemental ultra-fine mesh run (22 M cells) at the 7 L/min condition confirmed that the fine-mesh RH value is within 1.1% of the extrapolated value, providing additional assurance that the discretization effect on the regulatory conclusion is negligible."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions (fluid viscosity, temperature, hematocrit) documented and bracketing CFD boundary conditions.",
      "rationale": "FDA bench tests used porcine blood at 37 °C, hematocrit 33 ± 2%, and viscosity 3.2 ± 0.3 mPa·s. CFD inlet boundary conditions were set to match mean experimental values. Temperature variation effects were assessed via a sensitivity run showing less than 0.8% change in RH. Test conditions are adequately characterized for MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted RH values compared to experimental measurements with normalized error < 15% at all validated operating points.",
      "rationale": "CFD-predicted relative hemolysis index was compared against five experimental operating points from the FDA dataset. Normalized errors ranged from 2.3% to 11.7%, all within the 15% acceptance threshold. Agreement is consistent with published literature for similar turbomachinery hemolysis models."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
